    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Insult to Gun Owners</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Daniel Schmutter letter replies to May 24 Topics of The Times objecting to National Rifle Association's plan to open a theme restaurant in Times Square</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>''The N.R.A. in Times Square'' (Topics of The Times, May 24), objecting to the National Rifle Association's plan to open a theme restaurant in Times Square, declares that ''the last thing these kids need is somebody trying to disguise the fact that guns represent a tremendous public health threat.''</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>''The N.R.A. in Times Square'' (Topics of The Times, May 24), objecting to the National Rifle Association's plan to open a theme restaurant in Times Square, declares that ''the last thing these kids need is somebody trying to disguise the fact that guns represent a tremendous public health threat.''</p>
        <p>This implies that there is no difference between law-abiding gun owners and criminals. Firearms owned by law-abiding citizens have never been any sort of public health threat, and to suggest otherwise is insulting to tens of millions of honest Americans. This is like calling cars, which kill more Americans than guns, a tremendous public health threat because of drunk drivers and careless motorists.</p>
        <p>DANIEL SCHMUTTER  West Orange, N.J., May 24, 2000</p>
      </block>
